What I-A-M is: the authorization engine.

I-A-M, which stands for Identity and Access Management, is the service that decides, for every single A-P-I call, whether the caller is allowed to do what they're asking. A console click, a command line call, a boto-three call in your code: they all funnel through the same authorization engine before anything actually happens.

Three properties define it. First, it's global. There's no region selector. Your users, groups, roles, and policies exist account-wide, not per region. Second, it's default-deny. If no policy explicitly allows an action, that action is denied. Silence means no. And third, it's free. You never pay for I-A-M itself, only for the resources it grants access to.

I-A-M sits underneath every other AWS service. You don't turn it on; every request is already being evaluated by it. So the rest of this module is really about the vocabulary I-A-M gives you to answer one question precisely: who may do what, on which resource, and under which conditions.
